TI  - Skill of the High-Resolution WRF Rainfall Forecast by Dense Rain Gauge Network: A Case Study Over Karnataka, India
T2  - PURE AND APPLIED GEOPHYSICS
LA  - English
KW  - Dense rain gauge
KW  - WRF forecast
KW  - statistical scores
KW  - rainfall
AB  - The Karnataka State Natural Disaster and Management Centre (KSNDMC), Bangalore, India, provided real-time rainfall forecasts to the farmer community through an interactive call centre called Varuna Mitra operating 24x7, with weather modelling support from the Space Applications Centre, Indian Space Research Organisation (ISRO) Ahmedabad, India. The objective of this study is to assess the skill of the high-resolution rainfall prediction from the Weather Research and Forecasting (WRF) model using a dense rain gauge network over Karnataka, a state in southern peninsula India. Various spatial, temporal and categorical statistics are evaluated for heterogeneous geographical and weather conditions during the summer monsoon 2017-2020. Results suggested that the hit rate was similar to 71% at the 0.5 mm day(-1) rainfall threshold in 2017-2019, which increased slightly to similar to 72% in 2020. The probability of detection (POD) also improved from similar to 67% in 2017 to similar to 72% in 2020 over Karnataka state. Other statistical parameters including average bias were improved marginally in 2020. The miss rate and critical success index (CSI) scores suggested that the WRF rainfall predictions improved considerably in 2020. Over-forecast was 22% in 2017 and decreased to 20% in 2020. Overall, these statistics suggest that the WRF rainfall predictions have improved over the Karnataka state.
