TI  - Effects of sand mining for ring net fisheries on coastal ecosystem in Kunduchi, Dar es Salaam, Tanzania
T2  - MARINE POLLUTION BULLETIN
LA  - English
KW  - Sand mining
KW  - Ring net fisheries
KW  - Catches
KW  - Coastal ecosystem
KW  - Marine
KW  - Environment
KW  - SMALL-SCALE FISHERIES
KW  - MARINE PROTECTED AREAS
KW  - SUSTAINABILITY
KW  - POVERTY
AB  - The increasing use of sand as sinkers in ring-net fishing poses significant threats to coastal ecosystems and fish catches in Kunduchi. This study investigates the pressures, drivers, and effects of sand mining practices among local fishing communities and explores strategies for sustainable management. A mixed-methods approach was employed, combining primary data from interviews, focus group discussions, and field observations with secondary data from the Kinondoni Municipal Fisheries Database (2020-2022). Statistical analyses, including descriptive summaries and Principal Axis Factoring, were conducted using IBM SPSS version 20 and Microsoft Excel 2021. Key findings reveal that sand mining for ring net fisheries is driven by factors such as increased resource demand, inadequate law enforcement, and limited economic alternatives. These drivers contribute to adverse environmental and socioeconomic outcomes, including declining fish catches, coastal erosion, and pollution, with notable impacts on human wellbeing. Stakeholders, including Beach Management Units, government bodies, and NGOs, are involved in addressing these challenges but face significant limitations in controlling destructive practices. The study highlights the prevalence of sand mining for ring-net fishing along the coast of Kunduchi and underscores the need for integrated coastal management strategies. Recommendations include promoting innovative alternatives, such as using net sinkers instead of sand and strengthening surveillance in inshore waters. Additionally, empowering local fishers through targeted seminars and awareness campaigns is suggested to encourage sustainable fishing practices. These measures aim to mitigate environmental degradation, enhance the resilience of coastal ecosystems, and support the livelihoods of local fishing communities.
