AB  - The use of straw mulch to reduce soil and water losses is a common practice worldwide. However, when overland flow occurs under the mulch canopy, a critical shear stress results, and rills can be formed which can contribute to mulch failure. This study investigated the effect of rainfall intensity and slope gradient on rill initiation and development under mulch (0.8 kg m- 2). In addition, the effect of water quality on runoff and soil loss reductions was examined. Two typical soils of the Loess Plateau of China were packed into 5-m long flumes set at three different slope gradients, with each covered with mulch and subjected to 60-mm simulated rainstorms with different rainfall intensities (100, 140, and 180 mm h- 1). Rainwater quality was specified as either deionized water (DW) or tap water (TW). Under all conditions, total soil losses and total runoff were lower under the TW rainwater than under the DW rainwater. The water quality effect on runoff varied according to the discharge rate. As the discharge rate was increased from a low rate (starting from a low rainfall intensity or moderate slope) the DW increasingly reduced runoff in both soils. Whereas, when the discharge rate was relatively high, either under the highest rainfall intensity or on the steepest slope, the DW impact on runoff reduction declined with further increases in the discharge rate in the case of the silt loam soil, and responded erratically in the case of the clay loam soil. This implies that there is a critical discharge rate at which the water quality effect on runoff is maximized. Water quality also impacted soil loss and had the greatest effect under conditions where the slope was low, the rainfall rate was 180 mm h- 1, and when rills had not formed. In contrast to runoff reduction, when the discharge rate was relatively low, increases in the discharge rate in response to increases in slope or rainfall intensity resulted in decreased or little change in the soil loss reductions for the silt loam soil. When the discharge rate was relatively high, further increases in the discharge rate resulted in an increased water quality soil loss reduction effect. In contrast, for the clay loam soil the water quality effect increased with increases in slope or rainfall intensity. The soil loss reduction effect was likely complicated by the degree of rill formation, which occurred in both soils under mulch under all conditions except from the gentle slope. The use of TW rainwater, as compared to DW rainwater, delayed rill initiation so that it occurred lower down the slope and reduced the extent of rill development. This would reflect the effect of increased soil stability on rill initiation and development for the studied soils. The results suggest that when there is a risk of rill development under mulch, the use of an amendment that releases electrolytes under the mulch may be advisable to reduce runoff and soil losses. The results of this work can inform farmers with respect to agricultural practices in various slope and rainfall conditions in that sites may be more appropriately selected to limit run off and rill formation when considering flood and variable rainfall instances. This work also contributes to the diverse research which has identified the extent of the various factors that impact agriculture runoff, infiltration, surface impacts (rill formation), and soil loss, such as slope, water quality, and soil type. Mitigation measures such as straw application and other technologies can also be informed by these results.
