KW  - Sustainable development
KW  - Coastal governance
AB  - Marine Spatial Planning (MSP) is a strategic approach to managing human activities in coastal and marine areas to achieve ecological, economic, and social goals. This study recognizes multiple use conflicts in economic activities in Bhola and Hatia, two ecologically and economically important islands in Southern Bangladesh and reflects community perception in resolving these issues. The objectives of this study are to document sectoral overlaps, livelihood dependencies and conflict-prone areas, challenges and possible solutions that must be addressed before zoning and governance frameworks can be developed. A cross-sectional descriptive design was used, combining a household survey (n = 385), 16 focus-group discussions (FGDs), and 11 key-informant interviews (KIIs). Survey responses are summarized as frequencies and percentages, and qualitative notes are used to describe recurring themes and stakeholder-prioritized actions across fisheries, aquaculture, agriculture, and ecotourism. Results show high livelihood dependency on Agriculture (95.3 % Crop Farming and 89.6 % Vegetable Farming) and Fisheries (83.6 %). The major obstacles impairing the advancement of these sectors are illegal fishing, salinity intrusion, inadequate transport and tourism infrastructure. Stakeholders recommended stricter enforcement of fishing bans, establishing hatcheries and processing plants, improved supply chain and stronger disaster preparedness. This research provides crucial groundwork for establishing a comprehensive MSP in Bangladesh's coastal islands, by providing validated stakeholder insights and priorities which can guide the policymakers to develop strategies that balance economic growth with ecological sustainability in Bhola and Hatia.
