TI  - Assessment of water-cropland-grassland-livestock balance in the agro-pastoral ecotone in northern China under the grazing exclusion policy
T2  - AGRICULTURAL SYSTEMS
LA  - English
KW  - WCGL
KW  - Herbivorous livestock
KW  - Agro-pastoral ecotone
KW  - Grazing exclusion
KW  - Carrying capacity
AB  - Context: China's northern agro-pastoral ecotone serves as an important region for herbivorous livestock development, yet faces challenges including grassland degradation, insufficient crop-livestock system integration, water scarcity, and grazing exclusion impacts. Objective: Therefore, this research constructs a water-cropland-grassland-livestock (WCGL) balance assessment framework to evaluate whether water, cropland, and grassland resources can sustainably support herbivorous livestock production. Methods: This research employs an improved CASA model and multiple analytical methods, such as water footprint method. Results and conclusions: Key findings include: (1) Under grazing exclusion policies, cropland constitutes the primary forage source. The entire study area continues to experience severe overloading, but the significant increase in forage supply has alleviated this issue. Forage deficit overload is severe in most of the 19 cities, except for Xinzhou and Lvliang. Similarly, overload improved significantly in most cities during the study period. (2) Water consumption for herbivorous livestock primarily originates from cropland forage. Water-based overload remains severe across the study area with no significant temporal trend, yet exhibits spatial heterogeneity: conditions are less severe in the northeast than in the central and southwestern regions. (3) Overall, most cities face long-term dual forage and water deficit overload. (4) Reducing grazing exclusion intensity not only increases natural grass supply but also alleviates water pressure by decreasing cropland forage dependence when total supply exceeds demand. While partial cities may fully resolve forage or water deficits through such reductions, most remain overloaded even with complete exclusion lifting. Significance: This research offers a practical basis for optimizing resource use and supporting sustainable herbivorous livestock management.
