TI  - Typhoon Odette (Rai): Rapid intensification, devastation, and lessons for resilient recovery in the Philippines
T2  - TROPICAL CYCLONE RESEARCH AND REVIEW
LA  - English
KW  - NDRRMC
KW  - PAGASA
KW  - OCHA
KW  - DSWD
KW  - ILO
KW  - UNICEF
AB  - The study explored how Typhoon Odette developed, what made it so powerful, and how it deeply affected the lives of millions of Filipinos, disrupting homes, livelihoods, infrastructure, agriculture, and the economy. To ensure accuracy, data were drawn from trusted sources such as the National Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Council (NDRRMC), PAGASA, the United Nations OCHA Philippines, the Department of Social Welfare and Development (DSWD), the International Labour Organization (ILO-Philippines), and UNICEF Philippines. Accordingly, the study highlighted the typhoon's devastating impact when it struck in 2021. In particular, over 12 million people were affected, with more than 114,000 displaced. Meanwhile, in MIMAROPA, Regions V to XII, and Caraga, 405 lives were lost, 1371 were injured, and 52 went missing, many due to drowning. Furthermore, the typhoon caused severe damage across 98 flooded areas and 367 other incidents, destroyed nearly 2000 buildings worth almost PHP 30 billion, and crippled essential services such as electricity, water, transportation, and communication. In addition, more than 2 million homes were affected, and agricultural losses were estimated at PHP 17.7 billion. Similarly, the ILO reported that approximately 4.4 million workers, especially in Regions VI, VII, VIII, and XIII, suffered direct impacts, with women and informal workers among the hardest hit. Given its strength, with sustained winds of 195 kph and gusts reaching 270 kph, Odette ranked among the most powerful typhoons in recent years, prompting Signal No. 5 alerts. Therefore, based on these findings, the study recommended measures to improve disaster preparedness and response. Specifically, it emphasized the need to strengthen infrastructure, enhance early warning systems, provide targeted support for vulnerable workers, and foster better coordination among government agencies and humanitarian organizations so that the impact of future disasters may be minimized. (c) 