TI  - Incidence of water scarcity: understanding the triggers and implications for women's non-agricultural livelihoods in Northern Ghana
T2  - COGENT SOCIAL SCIENCES
LA  - English
KW  - Water scarcity
KW  - gender
KW  - feminist political ecology
KW  - non-agricultural livelihoods
KW  - northern Ghana
KW  - ENVIRONMENT
KW  - GENDER
AB  - Water scarcity has multiple negative repercussions for women across the world due to their gender role in sourcing and collecting water for household uses. While this is the case, the triggers of water scarcity and its implications for women's non-agricultural livelihoods in the East and West Mamprusi municipalities of northern Ghana are poorly understood in the literature. Guided by the feminist political ecology approach, and drawing on a triangulation mixed-method, involving a survey of 394 women, focus group discussions, and complemented with temperature data, this paper contributes to the body of knowledge by examining the triggers of water scarcity and its implications for women's non-agricultural livelihoods in northern Ghana. Findings revealed that although residents have limited water points, with some of them being unsafe for drinking, a combination of physical and human factors are adding woes to their water shortage. Again, women were found to be suffering unduly from the water shortages with multiple adverse repercussions for their non-agricultural livelihoods. These findings highlight not only the need for local governments to step up efforts in water provision, but also recognize the gendered effects of water shortage in the East and West Mamprusi municipalities of northern Ghana. IMPACT STATEMENT Water scarcity is becoming worse in northern Ghana, particularly in the West and East Mamprusi municipalities, as women and girls continue to compete for domestic water from the limited water points. Guided by the feminist political pcology, this study examined the triggers of water scarcity and its implications for women's non-agricultural livelihoods in the West and East Mamprusi municipalities. It was motivated by the pressing need to attain target 6.1 of the Sustainable Development Goal 6, of the United Nations, which seeks to achieve universal and equitable access to safe and affordable drinking water for all by 2030. The findings highlight that local governments need to prioritize water provision and recognize the gendered effects of water scarcity. Additionally, it offers community leaders and decision-makers with evidence-based guidance to boost the efficacy of planned or implemented initiatives intended to sustain water for diverse uses in northern Ghana.
