TI  - Social acceptance of water quality through decentralized greywater treatment using green wall system
T2  - GLOBAL JOURNAL OF ENVIRONMENTAL SCIENCE AND MANAGEMENT-GJESM
LA  - English
KW  - Community participation
KW  - Environmental management
KW  - Innovative systems
KW  - Social readiness
KW  - Sustainable solution
KW  - Water quality
AB  - BACKGROUND AND OBJECTIVES: Addressing water scarcity through innovative and sustainable solutions is crucial in regions like Jordan, where resources are limited, and community involvement plays a pivotal role in ensuring success. This study examines the social acceptance and readiness of university dormitory residents, specifically female students at Al-Zahra'a Dormitory, the University of Jordan, for implementing a decentralized greywater treatment system using green walls. This study seeks to examine the social factors influencing the deployment of decentralized greywater treatment systems, particularly focusing on enhancing public acceptance and ensuring their sustainable use in urban settings.METHODS:This study investigated the technical capabilities of the greywater treatment system by analyzing the quality of the treated effluent against Jordanian standards, thereby evaluating its potential for reuse in toilet flushing and irrigation applications. Additionally, a structured questionnaire with 24 questions was distributed to dormitory residents and staff to explore social acceptance. Responses were categorized into four thematic groups: 1) Awareness and Understanding, assessing participants' familiarity with greywater treatment; 2) Perceptions and Attitudes, evaluating opinions and concerns regarding the system; 3) Environmental Impact, examining perceived benefits and potential drawbacks; and 4) Participation and Support, measuring willingness to engage in operation and maintenance activities. This mixed-methods strategy offered in-depth understanding of the technical viability and social interactions involved in the implementation of the system. FINDINGS: The findings indicate that 90 percent of respondents are aware of water scarcity, with the majority strongly supporting innovative solutions like the green wall system. The study emphasizes the critical role of community participation in the success of sustainable systems. Notably, 82 percent of respondents expressed interest in training programs on the operation and maintenance of the greywater system, demonstrating a proactive attitude toward its long-term sustainability. Morever, 87 percent favored the expansion of the system from the dormitory to other residential neighborhoods, reflecting a strong consensus and the potential for more extensive application. However, concerns regarding potential issues such as odor and health impacts were noted, with nearly 50 percent of participants expressing discomfort. CONCLUSION: Overall, strong community interest and readiness for green wall-based greywater systems highlight their potential to address water challenges. Continuous monitoring, system optimization, and stakeholder collaboration are essential for long-term success. By implementing well-defined protocols, offering thorough training, and optimizing management strategies, organizations can alleviate health and environmental concerns, which in turn cultivates trust among users. Expanding these systems to other areas with community involvement and outreach programs can amplify impact. Continued investigation into social acceptance will improve strategies and promote the broader implementation of decentralized greywater treatment solutions
